        {
          "username": "Roberta Newman",
          "rating": 5,
          "contributor_id": "115008115824228895354",
          "user_review_count": 10,
          "user_photo_count": 0,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjU_kYClPNrgFXbF4bFNNq03aqkRnhgUIhxj38fFjRUx_a3OBOpj=s120-c-rp-mo-ba12-br100",
          "description": "I was apprehensive when I was told the ambulance was taking my 90-year-old mother to Metropolitan. She is wheelchair-bound but was accidentally rolled off her bed and hit and gashed her head. I didn't know what to expect. But I was pleasantly surprised. Over the past 15-20 years I've been in ERs in different hospitals about 20 times and I'm a real connoisseur at this point. The staff at Metropolitan was nicer, more proactive, and more responsive than at any other hospital I've experienced. I didn't have to badger them for information -- they came to us! (Those of you who have been in ERs will understand the reason for my exclamation point.) The doctor came to see her 3 times during his shift. We waited less time for the results of her CAT scan than we would have at upscale Weill Cornell. We were there from about 9:00 pm to 7:30 am. We were actually discharged an hour or two before but we had to wait for an ambulette to get her back to her facility.  This ER isn't pretty or spiffy-looking but the staff knows their stuff and their dedication and devotion to their work really shows.",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sCi9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2tkb2MzVXdZMmsyZFdweWVVbzVXRUV3VVRVMFVuYxAB!2m1!1s0x0:0x109f241bdc20e3a!3m1!1s2@1:CAIQACodChtycF9oOkdoc3UwY2k2dWpyeUo5WEEwUTU0Unc%7C%7C?hl=en",
          "date": "11 months ago",
