        },
        {
          "username": "Kim Foulds",
          "rating": 2,
          "contributor_id": "103922771525601705959",
          "user_review_count": 52,
          "user_photo_count": 4,
          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/ALV-UjW7Q2Sq9B3YXI_irjq3_KAGO_dI7loofDGLWxNF7LAiFvExRaY=s120-c-rp-mo-ba12-br100",
          "description": "I went to the ER on Dec 15.  The intake and nursing staff were great. My review is for Dr. Trisha Paul who seemed to not believe I was in pain, noting that my abnormal blood test wasn\u2019t abnormal enough. Given my complaints, an abdominal ultrasound should have been standard. But I was given Pepcid and a pain med and let go. I ended up back at the ER, Mount Sinai this time, on 12/24 and had an emergency gallbladder removal on 12/25. I was in the worst pain of my life for 10 days, all of which could have been addressed earlier had Dr. Paul taken my complaints seriously. The silver lining of this negligence is that I didn\u2019t then have to have surgery at Metropolitan and was able to get excellent care from the Mount Sinai team.\n\nI write this because I hope this gets back to her. Given Dr. Paul\u2019s interest in pediatric oncology, I want to stress the importance of believing your patients. I could advocate for myself and she still did not care. Most children do not have the same abilities. Please take what your patients are telling you seriously.",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSUNma3N1ZVpnEAE!2m1!1s0x0:0x109f241bdc20e3a!3m1!1s2@1:CIHM0ogKEICAgICfksueZg%7C%7C?hl=en",
